recordings.type: alarm call, aircraft noise just at the loudest part of the interaction
recordings.rmk:
The male was reacting to the presence of a newly arrived female, very anxious about her arriving here; this type of call is given when chicks are very small, as well as when alarmed in this sort of situation. It is very deep toned and grunting, best listened to through headphones, he calls some 4 times in this cut, with very short preamble grunts in a couple of cases.
The female was calling for him yesterday, a higher pitched less grunting version, but I missed the chance to tape her, getting female calls is extremely challenging as they are so infrequent.

recordings.rmk: Over the past few days I spent several hours trying to tape the deep infrasonic 3 or 4 syllabled "departure call" of our male Cassowary, which he gives once or maybe twice each visit, over a couple of hours stay, and only in the mornings oddly enough.  He bows his head and fluffs out the neck and back feathers to give this very deep rolling grunt, which you can feel in the pit of your stomach. I finally got it this morning, with him just below me off our veranda, but when I play back the ME 66 Sennheiser mike does not seem to have picked it up! Very disappointing

recordings.loc: Ferries McDonald Conservation Park, Murray Bridge, South Australia
recordings.rmk: Duet between male (lower pitched booming calls) and female (higher-pitched drawn-out and rising calls). Not certain whether the quieter 'oom' sounds in the background are also Malleefowl pair contact calls, or Common Bronzewings, but the former is quite possible. P. Menkhorst et alia, The Australian Bird Guide (CSIRO Publishing, Melbourne, 2019, p. 212), have the following to say about the voice of Malleefowl: "Mostly silent: soft 'ooom' contact calls between pair. Male territorial call is a loud booming 'uh-uh-uh oom-oom-oom' made with head bowed beneath the chest. The male boom call may be given in duet with a drawn-out, high pitched and rising 'waugh-waugh' given by female."

recordings.file-name: XC692675-Marbled Frogmouth Portland Road IR Dec 15 2200 very faint edit PG1679.mp3
recordings.rmk:
This bird was singing not far from where we were in the dense rainforest, it sounded quite close but the recording is rather faint. It is not the usual "koo loo" series often give as a duet.
The taxonomy of this species badly needs re-evlauating as some taxa such as meeki seem to have very distinct vocalizations, and all the New Guinea ones seem somewhat different to the Australian taxa

Recorded on iPhone.

recordings.loc: Bateau Bay, Wyong Shire Council, New South Wales
recordings.rmk:
Initially thought this was a Fox calling in the distance, however, could then see the Frogmouth perched in overhead branch calling. Haven’t heard this call previously and I suspect it was a juvenile as the Frogmouths had bred a few weeks earlier in the same tree. Did not have a spotlight and could not confirm if it was actually a juvenile, Call continued for about three minutes, before it flew to another branch and continued calling for  another two minutes 
Recording was on iPhone and the original recording has been cut to omit background voices.

recordings.loc: Native Gap Conservation Reserve (near  Anmatjere), Central Desert Shire, Northern Territory
recordings.rmk: This is from a long ARU recording. I originally thought that the snatch of Spotted Nightjar in this recording was mimicry by the Pied Butcherbird which follows on immediately. I now think that it is actually a Spotted Nightjar but either the mic missed the first part of its call (the 'woop-woop-woop') or the bird didn't utter it. The Pied Butcherbird song which follows it shortly afterwards is merely a coincidence. Happy to receive correspondence from anyone with other thoughts.
